Dakarai Mashava FEATURES & MAGAZINES EDITOR ZIMBABWE’S funeral services sector’s capacity to handle rising Covid-19 deaths will come under the spotlight in an online discussion forum to be convened by Associated Newspapers of Zimbabwe (ANZ) via Zoom on Thursday. To be co-hosted in conjunction with the Zimbabwe Association of Funeral Assurers (Zafa), the discussion comes in the wake of the debilitating effects of the second wave of Covid-19 whose rate of infections and death toll have reached alarming levels. As such, funeral directors are overwhelmed by the pandemic which may precipitate the industry’s collapse unless urgent interventions are made to save the situation. Lewis Chikurunhe, the commercial director for the ANZ — publishers of the Daily News and the Daily News on Sunday, said it has become urgent for industry stakeholders to put their heads together to chart the way forward. “The Webinar is coming at a time Zimbabwe’s funeral industry is facing unprecedented challenges. “The period between April 2020 and now has been wearisome for the industry as everything that shouldn’t have gone wrong, has gone adrift,” he said.  “The rising death toll has meant that the industry is now overwhelmed and reaching a point of incapacitation to deal with the tragedy. “Since the onset of the second wave, there is now realisation that the years of investment made in infrastructure by players in the industry is hardly adequate to deal with a pandemic of this magnitude,” added Chikurunhe, while opining that practical measures have to be urgently implemented by all concerned stakeholders to salvage the situation. Chikurunhe expressed hope that the Webinar would come up with useful recommendations to rescue the funeral sector. “Our Events Division rarely misses the opportunity to play its part in promoting dialogue and coming up with solutions to critical national issues. “We, therefore, expect players in the industry to participate in their numbers, speak with one voice and reason with the government on how we can navigate this crisis in the industry,” said Chikurunhe. The discussion forum thus aims to come up with recommendations that could guarantee the survival of the sector that has been stretched to near-breaking point by financial pressures caused by the Covid-19 pandemic.          googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1588599181508-1'); });      Apart from auditing the state of the funeral sector, the Webinar, to run under the theme ‘‘Dealing with headwinds in the funeral sector under Covid-19,’’ will also look at the legal and regulatory frameworks guiding the sector as well as Covid-19 regulations and the safety of staff. Organisers of the discussion forum have put together a high powered panel that includes Grace Muradzikwa from the Insurance and Pensions Commission, Nyaradzo Funeral services general manager Batsirai Simango, Zafa president Solomon Chikanda, Doves managing director Talent Maziwisa and Harare City Council health services director Prosper Chonzi. Sponsored Links                                              Classifieds.co.zw                                                                                                                      Property, Houses                                                                                                                                                      Building Supplies                                                                                                                                                      Electronics                                                                                                                                                      Cars                                                                                                                                                      Home & Garden                                                                                                         